#include <iostream>
#include <cstdlib>
using namespace std;

class Test
{
private:
    int m_x;

public:
    Test(int val = 0) : m_x(val) {}

    // Overload new
    static void* operator new(size_t size) ****most imp point is its static 
    {
        cout << "Overloaded new" << endl;

        void* ptr = malloc(size);

        if (ptr == nullptr)
            throw bad_alloc();

        return ptr;
    }

    // Overload delete
    static void operator delete(void* ptr) *** static 
    {
        cout << "Overloaded delete" << endl;
        free(ptr);
    }
};

int main()
{
    Test* p = new Test(34);

    delete p;

    return 0;
}


Q. Why overload new/delete?
A. To customize memory allocation and deallocation.

Q. Why are operator new/delete static? *********************VVVVVVIMP
operator new() is called before an object is created.

At that time, there is no object, so there is no 'this' pointer.

Therefore, operator new() cannot be a non-static member function.

Similarly, operator delete() is called after the object has been destroyed, so it also cannot rely on a valid 'this' pointer.

Hence, operator new() and operator delete() are declared static.

operator new()      ← No object exists yet  ****IIIIMP
        ↓
Memory allocated
        ↓
Constructor
        ↓
Object created

Notice that when operator new() is called:

❌ Object does not exist
❌ No this pointer

So it must be static.

Q. Does operator new construct the object?
A. No. It only allocates raw memory.

Q. Does operator delete destroy the object?
A. No. The destructor runs first, then operator delete
releases the memory.

Execution Order:

new:
operator new() -> Constructor

delete:
Destructor -> operator delete()

Q. Why throw bad_alloc?
A. Standard C++ new throws std::bad_alloc if memory allocation fails.

******* glocal scope****
#include <iostream>
#include <cstdlib>
using namespace std;

void* operator new(size_t size)
{
    cout << "Global new\n";

    void* ptr = malloc(size);

    if(ptr == nullptr)
        throw bad_alloc();

    return ptr;
}

void operator delete(void* ptr)
{
    cout << "Global delete\n";
    free(ptr);
}

